# Full verse-by-verse coverage — Matthew 5–6
MATTHEW_5_6 = {
  "5": {
    "1": '<p>A type: Jesus ascending the mountain to deliver the kingdom-Torah mirrors Moses ascending Sinai to receive the Law (Exod 19:3; 24:12). Matthew has been constructing this New Moses typology from the flight to Egypt and back (2:14–15), the crossing of water at baptism, the forty-day testing in the wilderness. The mountain-seat is the throne of the authoritative teacher; but unlike Moses, Jesus will speak on his own authority.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "he opened his mouth and taught them" echoes the formal opening of authoritative divine speech. The content that follows is not Torah transmitted but the announcement of what the Law always aimed at — the life of the kingdom as Christ embodies it. The Teacher here is also the subject of the teaching.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A fulfillment: Luke 4:18–19 records Jesus citing Isa 61:1–2 ("he has anointed me to preach good news to the poor") as fulfilled in himself. The first beatitude draws on the same Isaianic tradition of the <em>anawim</em> — the poor, humble ones who receive God\'s favor. The kingdom of heaven belongs to those who know they cannot bring it about; Christ is the one who brings it to them.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A fulfillment: Isa 61:2–3 promised that the anointed one would "comfort all who mourn" and give them "a garland instead of ashes." The comfort is eschatological — it arrives with the Messiah. This beatitude is not advice for managing grief but an announcement that the one who comforts has come.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A fulfillment: Ps 37:11 ("the meek shall inherit the land") is a promise to the faithful remnant who trust God rather than seize by force. The NT reading is that the land-promise has been expanded to the whole renewed creation (Rom 4:13), and the meek who receive it are those who enter the kingdom Christ opens. The inheritance comes through him, not through them.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A fulfillment: Isa 55:1–2 invites the thirsty and hungry to come and eat what only God can give — covenant satisfaction that money cannot buy. The beatitude draws on that Isaianic promise and announces its arrival. Christ is both the one who pronounces the blessing and, as the righteous one, the ground of the righteousness his people receive (2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
    "7": '<p>The theme of <em>hesed</em> — covenant mercy — runs from Exod 34:6–7 through the Psalms and Prophets as the defining attribute of God toward his covenant people. The beatitude promises that those who embody this mercy will receive it. Christ is the definitive demonstration of divine mercy (Rom 9:15–16) and the one through whom his people become merciful.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A fulfillment: Ps 24:3–4 asks who may ascend the hill of the LORD — "he who has clean hands and a pure heart." The beatitude echoes this entrance criterion and announces its fulfillment: the pure in heart will see God. This eschatological vision is made possible through Christ who purifies the heart (Acts 15:9; Heb 10:22) and is himself the image of the invisible God (Col 1:15).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: peacemakers are called sons of God because they reflect the character of the God who reconciles. The NT identifies Christ as the <em>eirēnopoiēsas</em>, the one who makes peace through the blood of his cross (Col 1:20). Those who make peace share in the family vocation of God\'s firstborn Son (Rom 8:29).</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme: the prophets were persecuted for righteousness, and so is the Servant of Isaiah (Isa 50:6; 53:3). The kingdom of heaven belongs to the persecuted because they belong to the suffering Servant who has already entered the kingdom through suffering. Persecution for righteousness is participation in the pattern Christ established (1 Pet 2:21).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A direct claim: the shift to second person ("blessed are <em>you</em>") and the explicit "because of me" makes this a Christological criterion. Persecution that qualifies for the beatitude is specifically suffering on account of Jesus — not suffering in general, but suffering caused by alignment with him. The blessedness is constituted by relationship to his person.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: the long tradition of prophetic suffering (1 Kgs 18:4; Neh 9:26; Jer 20) is the lineage the disciples enter. Christ stands at the end of that line as the prophet par excellence who was rejected and killed (Matt 21:37–39). Rejoicing in persecution is possible because the pattern ends not in death but in vindication — as Christ\'s own resurrection demonstrates.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme: Israel was called to be a covenant community seasoning the world with divine righteousness (cf. the salt of the covenant, Num 18:19; Lev 2:13). The disciple community now carries this vocation through Christ, who himself is the covenant salt (Mark 9:49–50). Saltiness that cannot be restored mirrors the covenant that cannot be renewed by human effort — it requires the renewing work of Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: Isaiah\'s Servant is appointed "a light to the nations" (Isa 42:6; 49:6), and Jesus applies this Servant vocation to his disciple community. But John\'s Gospel identifies Jesus himself as the light of the world (John 8:12; 9:5). The disciples are derivative light — they illuminate because he does. A city on a hill cannot be hidden; neither can the one who brought it into being.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme: the lamp-on-stand image is proverbial wisdom, but its Christological weight lies in what the lamp reveals. The light that must not be hidden is ultimately the light of the knowledge of the glory of God displayed in the face of Christ (2 Cor 4:6). The community bears this light; Christ is its source.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: the goal of visible good works is the glorification of the Father, not self-commendation. This is the pattern Jesus models throughout his ministry — everything he does points to the Father (John 5:19; 8:29). The disciple community, formed by Christ, continues his doxological mission.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct revelation: I have not come to abolish the Law and the Prophets but to <em>plēroō</em> (fulfill). Christ\'s relationship to Scripture is unique: he is not a scribe who interprets it, not a prophet who applies it, but the one toward whom all of it was pointing and in whom all of it reaches its intended fullness. The antitheses that follow (you have heard it said... but I say to you) demonstrate Jesus\'s sovereign authority to reveal the Torah\'s deepest intention — the intention the Author always had, which only the Author himself can fully declare. Paul states the same: "Christ is the <em>telos</em> of the law" (Rom 10:4).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: not one iota or serif will pass from the Law "until all is accomplished" (<em>heōs an panta genētai</em>) — binding the Law\'s fulfillment to a historical completion event. The cross is where "it is finished" (<em>tetelestai</em>, John 19:30) and where the Law\'s demands are fully met (Col 2:14). The permanence of Torah is guaranteed by the one who fulfills it completely.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: the kingdom of heaven operates under the commands Christ delivers and interprets. Those who set aside the least of these commands misunderstand who gave them and who fulfills them. Greatness in this kingdom is calibrated by faithfulness to the one who embodies all righteousness.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct claim: the righteousness that exceeds the scribes and Pharisees is not quantitatively more rule-keeping but a different kind of righteousness altogether — the gift of right standing that comes through Christ (Phil 3:9; 2 Cor 5:21). Jesus announces the standard of the kingdom he is establishing, a standard only he can meet and only he can impart.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus quotes the sixth commandment (Exod 20:13) and extends it on his own authority — "But I say to you." This is not the prophetic formula (<em>thus says the LORD</em>) but the voice of the one who gave the Law. The antitheses do not set Torah aside; they reveal what it always required from the one who alone can see the heart.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: inward anger and contemptuous speech are subject to the same judgment as murder because Christ reveals the interior dimension of the commandment. The one who says "You fool!" faces Gehenna — language that only makes sense from the lips of the judge who knows the heart. Jesus speaks as the one who will adjudicate these very matters (Matt 25:31–46).</p>',
    "23": '<p>A theme: reconciliation placed above cultic worship is a consistent prophetic priority (Isa 1:13–17; Hos 6:6). Christ, who is both priest and sacrifice in the final offering (Heb 10:10), is also the one who provides the ultimate basis for human reconciliation (Eph 2:14–16). The altar-gift instruction points toward the offering that makes all reconciliation possible.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme: reconciliation precedes offering — the sequence that the sacrificial system aimed toward but could not achieve. The pattern points forward to the one who would be both the reconciling act and the offering: Christ\'s death is simultaneously the means of reconciliation with God and the foundation of human reconciliation (2 Cor 5:18–19).</p>',
    "25": '<p>A theme: the urgency of settling with one\'s adversary before reaching the judge reflects the eschatological urgency that runs through the Sermon — the kingdom is present, the Judge is already active. This urgency is anchored in who Jesus is: the coming Judge whose arrival makes the moment decisive.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A theme: the prison from which there is no exit until the last penny is paid is eschatological consequence-language — the seriousness of unresolved sin before the judgment Christ will execute. The way of escape is the way of reconciliation, the very thing Christ provides through his atoning work (Matt 26:28).</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: the seventh commandment (Exod 20:14) is quoted as the baseline from which Jesus will move to the interior. As with 5:21, the voice that extends the commandment is the same voice that gave it. The sequence — you have heard, but I say — identifies Jesus with the divine legislator who alone can authorize such an extension.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: lustful looking is adultery in the heart because Christ, who gave the command, sees the heart (1 Sam 16:7; Jer 17:10). This is not a new external rule but a revelation of what the commandment always addressed — the will oriented toward another person as an object. The standard is the standard of God\'s own purity, which only Christ fully embodies.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A theme: the hyperbolic language ("gouge out," "cut off") is not literal surgery but radical prioritization of the kingdom over bodily comfort. Christ embodies the ultimate sacrifice of body for the sake of others — the cross where his own body is given so that his people are not thrown into Gehenna. The logic of self-sacrifice he teaches here he enacts completely.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A theme: no part of the body is worth preserving at the cost of losing everything. This is the economics of the kingdom that Christ teaches and embodies: lose your life to save it (Matt 16:25). The one who calls his disciples to this radical calculus has himself paid the full cost.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme: Jesus engages the Mosaic divorce regulation (Deut 24:1–4) not to abolish it but to restrict it to its intended scope, restoring the creation order of Gen 1–2 that divorce disrupts (Matt 19:4–6). Christ as the new Adam restores what the old Adam lost — including the integrity of the covenant bond that marriage images.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: the exception clause and the adultery-consequence reveal Christ\'s understanding of marriage as a covenant bond (Mal 2:14–16) that cannot be dissolved without covenantal rupture. This mirrors the faithfulness of God to his covenant people — the divorce God declares in Jer 3:8 is the extreme end of covenant violation, not the norm. Christ upholds the covenant logic of permanence.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: the oath-system built on Lev 19:12 and Num 30:2 invoked divine witness to guarantee human speech. Jesus will now replace the entire apparatus with the truthfulness that characterizes life in God\'s kingdom — which Christ himself perfectly embodies ("I am the truth," John 14:6).</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "do not swear at all" removes the distinction between sacred and secular speech — every word is already spoken before God. Christ teaches an integrated integrity that he models completely. No oath can add to the truth of what God\'s own Son speaks.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A theme: the earth as God\'s footstool and Jerusalem as the city of the Great King (Ps 48:2) frame the prohibition in God\'s universal sovereignty. That sovereignty is not invoked by oath formulas but by life-orientation toward the King. The kingdom Jesus announces is the in-breaking of this reign — and Jesus is the one in whom the King arrives (Matt 21:5).</p>',
    "36": '<p>A theme: the inability to make a single hair white or black reveals human finitude before the divine absolute. Jesus grounds the prohibition of self-invoking oaths in the reality that humans have nothing to swear by. The one who speaks here is the one through whom every hair is numbered (Matt 10:30) — the difference between creature and Creator which the oath-system was meant to honor.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "let your yes be yes and your no be no" is the speech of one who needs no external guarantor because their words are self-authenticating. Jesus speaks this way throughout the Sermon — not "God has said" but "I say to you." His own yes is absolute (2 Cor 1:19–20: "all the promises of God are Yes in Christ").</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: the lex talionis (Exod 21:24; Lev 24:20; Deut 19:21) originally capped disproportionate retaliation. Jesus now replaces even the capped retaliation with non-resistance — absorbing evil rather than matching it. This is the movement of the cross, where God in Christ bears the full weight of human violence without retaliation (1 Pet 2:23).</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: "do not resist an evil person" is the ethics of the one who will not resist arrest, beating, or crucifixion (Matt 26:52–54). The right cheek turned is the right cheek Jesus turns in the passion. What he commands his disciples to embody, he enacts in the most extreme form. Non-retaliation is not passivity but the power of the God who overcomes evil with good (Rom 12:21).</p>',
    "40": '<p>A theme: giving the coat as well as the shirt inverts the logic of acquisition. The disciple community embodies the generosity by which Christ "though he was rich, became poor" so that others might be enriched (2 Cor 8:9). The ethics of kingdom generosity are grounded in what Christ himself does.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A theme: the compelled second mile converts legal obligation into an opportunity for grace — seizing occasion for generosity within or beyond compulsion. Christ goes the ultimate second mile by giving not just his labor but his life; this is the spirit that forms his community.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A revelation of God: "give to the one who asks you" reflects the character of the Father who gives to all who ask (Matt 7:11), and who gives without restraint in the gift of his Son (John 3:16). The disciple who gives freely participates in the generosity of God that is fully expressed in Christ.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: the command "love your neighbor" (Lev 19:18) had been narrowed in popular interpretation to the in-group. Jesus corrects both the misreading and the underlying logic. The one who delivers this teaching will define his enemies as those for whom he prays and dies (Luke 23:34; Rom 5:10).</p>',
    "44": '<p>A direct claim: "love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you" is the ethics that Christ embodies completely at the cross. He does not merely teach enemy-love as an abstract principle; he enacts it in the most extreme case (Luke 23:34; Rom 5:8). The command is not separable from the one who gives it and models it.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: the Father sends sun and rain on the evil and the good — providential indiscriminate care reflecting divine generosity unconditioned by desert. This is the character of God that Christ reveals (John 1:14, 18) and that his people are called to reflect. The Father\'s impartial provision is the ground of enemy-love, not merely its analogy.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A theme: the tax collectors are used as the baseline of reciprocal love — even the marginalized can love those who love them back. Christ befriends tax collectors (Matt 9:10–11) not because they love him first but because he loves them first (1 John 4:19), modeling the beyond-reciprocal love he demands.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A theme: even Gentiles greet their own. The disciple community is to embody a quality of relationship that crosses ethnic, social, and religious boundaries — which is precisely what Christ\'s mission accomplishes (Matt 28:19; Gal 3:28). The Sermon already anticipates the Gentile inclusion that Jesus brings.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A direct claim: "be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect" (<em>teleios</em>) echoes the Holiness Code\'s <em>imitatio Dei</em> ("be holy as I am holy," Lev 19:2) but uses the perfection-language that the NT applies to Christ\'s completed work (Heb 5:9; 7:28). The standard is the Father\'s own character, which only Christ fully embodies — and which he imparts to his people through the Spirit. This is not a demand satisfied by effort but a telos accomplished in him.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: the entire piety section (6:1–18) is organized around the contrast between performance before human observers and integrity before the Father. This is the covenant-loyalty distinction the prophets repeated (Isa 1:13–17; Jer 7:21–23). Christ fulfills this prophetic critique by being the perfectly sincere worshiper — every act of his public ministry done for the Father\'s glory, not human approval (John 5:41; 8:50).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: the trumpet-announcing gift is the hypocrite\'s bid for human honor in a culture where public beneficence was a recognized path to social standing. Jesus introduces a rival economy — the Father\'s recognition, which is neither visible nor revocable. Christ himself practiced this secrecy: healings done in private, instructions to tell no one (Matt 8:4; 9:30). The kingdom operates by a different exchange rate.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: "do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing" demands the absence of self-congratulation. The one who teaches this secret giving washed feet without announcement (John 13:4–5) and will give his life without fanfare (Isa 53:2–3). The ethics of hiddenness reflect the hidden life of the Son who "did not come to be served but to serve" (Matt 20:28).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of God: "your Father who sees in secret will reward you" — the Father\'s seeing is the foundational claim: God\'s knowledge is not limited to the observable. This is the ground of genuine piety and the reversal of every human honor system. The reward is the Father\'s recognition, made available through Christ who has fully revealed the Father (John 1:18; 17:6).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A theme: the synagogue-corner prayer is condemned not as prayer but as performance — piety shaped by human audience. Christ prays with intense hiddenness (Matt 14:23; 26:36–39) always in the posture of the Son speaking to the Father, which is the model he now offers his disciples.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: the inner room (<em>tameion</em>) prayer enacts one-on-one intimacy with the Father who is "unseen." This is the intimacy Christ models in Gethsemane and makes available by teaching his disciples to call God "Father." The door-closing mirrors the posture of the Son who lived in undivided communion with the Father (John 10:30; 17:21).</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: the pagan prayer-model assumes a deity who must be convinced or worn down. The Father Jesus reveals is not like this — he already knows what is needed before the asking. This is the God revealed in Christ who "searches the heart" (Rom 8:27) and whose Spirit intercedes with groanings too deep for words. Prayer is not information-delivery but relationship.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "your Father knows what you need before you ask him" removes anxiety about the adequacy of prayer. The Father\'s prior knowledge does not make prayer superfluous but reframes it as relational expression, not persuasion-mechanism. Christ makes this relationship available; his death removes every barrier to the Father\'s presence (Heb 10:19–22).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A direct claim: the Lord\'s Prayer opens with <em>Pater hēmōn</em> — "our Father in heaven." Jesus teaches his disciples to use the intimacy-word that defines his own relationship with God (Matt 11:27; John 20:17). Calling God "Father" is a Christological act — possible only because of who Jesus is and what he will accomplish. "Hallowed be your name" takes up the prophetic vision of Ezek 36:23 (God\'s eschatological name-vindication), which Jesus embodies and enacts.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A direct claim: "your kingdom come" is the prayer for what Jesus announces he brings (Matt 4:17; 12:28). Praying for the kingdom is praying for the completion of Christ\'s mission. "Your will be done on earth as in heaven" is the alignment of earthly reality with the heavenly order that the Incarnation makes possible — the Son who does only what he sees the Father doing (John 5:19) now teaches his people to pray for the same alignment.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme: daily bread echoes the manna in the wilderness (Exod 16:4) — God\'s daily provision that could not be stored up. The prayer for bread is the prayer of creatures who trust the Creator\'s daily faithfulness. Christ is himself the bread from heaven (John 6:35, 48–51) who provides what the manna only signified: life for the age to come.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme: the debt-forgiveness petition draws on the Jubilee logic of Lev 25 — the cancellation of debts as a sign of the covenant year. Christ enacts the ultimate Jubilee debt-cancellation through the cross (Col 2:13–14: "the written code that stood against us, he set aside, nailing it to the cross"). Praying for forgiveness is entering the economy Christ establishes.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct claim: "deliver us from the evil one" (<em>apo tou ponērou</em>) is the petition that Jesus himself enacts throughout his ministry — defeating temptation (Matt 4:1–11) and at the cross binding the strong man (Matt 12:29). The doxology ("yours is the kingdom, the power, and the glory") is the eschatological declaration that the kingdom Christ brings will not be overthrown.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: forgiveness extended to others is evidence that one has received the forgiveness Christ provides. The causal connection is not earning but consistency: those who refuse to forgive reveal that they have not internalized the divine mercy extended to them in Christ (cf. the unmerciful servant, Matt 18:21–35). The Father\'s forgiveness, made available through the Son\'s atoning work, is the well from which the community draws.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: withholding forgiveness while expecting it from the Father reveals an incoherent posture toward grace. Christ models the limit-case: forgiving those who crucify him (Luke 23:34), setting the ceiling on what forgiveness looks like. His community is defined by this overflow.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme: fasting was a recognized Second Temple piety practice. Jesus does not abolish it but reorients it away from visible demonstration. The disciples are those who will fast when the bridegroom is taken away (Matt 9:15) — a veiled reference to the passion. The fasting commended here is the mourning of those who long for what only Christ brings.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: anointing the head and washing the face — signs of celebration rather than mourning — are the outward normal while the inward fast continues. God, who sees the hidden heart, honors the hidden fast. Christ lives in this pattern: his inward devotion to the Father is complete and undivided even when outwardly present at feasts (John 2:1–11; Matt 11:19).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "your Father who sees in secret will reward you" closes the three-fold piety section (6:1–18) with the same foundational claim. The Father\'s seeing is the fixed point around which all authentic piety orbits — the God whom Christ reveals: not a public deity requiring visible performance, but the Father who exists in intimate relation with the Son and, through the Son, with his people.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: the prohibition of earthly treasure-storage grounds in kingdom logic: moths, rust, and thieves reveal the instability-principle of earthly wealth. The alternative — treasure in heaven — is the reorientation of all investment toward the kingdom Christ inaugurates. He himself, "though rich, became poor" (2 Cor 8:9) so that his people could become rich toward God.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme: heaven as the indestructible storehouse is the space of God\'s reign where Christ himself is now enthroned (Acts 2:33; Heb 1:3). Storing treasure there means investing in what Christ\'s resurrection has validated as permanent. The resurrection of Jesus is the guarantee that heavenly treasure is not metaphor but the only truly durable wealth.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "where your treasure is, there your heart will be also" is an anthropological claim about how the human heart works — it orients itself around what it most values. Christ models the perfectly God-oriented heart (John 4:34: "my food is to do the will of him who sent me"). His community is called to the same orientation: treasuring the kingdom above all else.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: the healthy eye (<em>haplous</em>, "single" or "undivided") that fills the body with light parallels the single-hearted devotion to God that is the Sermon\'s recurring concern. Christ is described as having the undivided Spirit resting on him (Matt 3:16), the one in whom the lamp burns without flicker. The community of disciples shares in this light by belonging to him.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: if the "light" within is actually darkness, the spiritual condition is worse than ordinary blindness — self-deception compounding error. This is Christ\'s diagnosis of the Pharisees who are outwardly luminous but inwardly dark (Matt 23:27–28). He is the diagnostic light who exposes the darkness by his presence (John 3:20–21; 1:9) and the true light who illuminates the path to the Father.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct claim: "you cannot serve both God and Money" applies the exclusive covenant loyalty of the Shema (Deut 6:4–5) to the specific temptation of wealth — the Elijah-challenge applied to mammon (1 Kgs 18:21). Jesus presents himself as the master who accepts no rival: following him requires leaving nets, tax booths, and wealth (Matt 4:20; 9:9; 19:21). He is the master who demands and receives exclusive allegiance.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: the prohibition of anxiety (<em>merimnate</em>) is grounded in the Father\'s providential character. Christ\'s provision enacts this care eschatologically — he feeds thousands in the wilderness (Matt 14:13–21; 15:32–38), mirroring and exceeding Elijah\'s miraculous feeding (1 Kgs 17:4–6). "Life is more than food" echoes Deut 8:3: human beings live not by bread alone but by every word from God\'s mouth — the word that Christ himself is (John 1:1).</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: the birds of the air that the heavenly Father feeds are the lesser case; the image-bearers are the greater. Christ embodies in history what the Father does in creation — feeding multitudes with nothing (Matt 14:19–20), enacting the Father\'s provision as flesh. To trust the Father\'s care is to trust the one through whom all things were created and are sustained (Col 1:16–17).</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "which of you by worrying can add a single cubit to his lifespan?" exposes the illusion of anxious control. Only God gives life; only Christ "has the words of eternal life" (John 6:68). The argument for non-anxiety is ultimately an argument about who holds the future — and the answer is the Father who sent the Son.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A theme: the flowers of the field neither labor nor spin yet are clothed by the Father\'s creative generosity. Jesus\'s observational attention to the created order reflects the wisdom tradition, but grounds it in the character of the Father whose creation reveals his care — the same Father that Christ makes known (John 1:3; Col 1:16–17).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: "not even Solomon in all his splendor was clothed like one of these" overturns the high point of Israelite material achievement. Solomon\'s glory was the peak of human provision-by-effort; the lily\'s glory is freely given by the Creator. The one who says this is greater than Solomon (Matt 12:42), and the kingdom he brings exceeds what Solomon\'s temple represented — the permanent dwelling of God with his people.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: the <em>oligopistoi</em> — those of "little faith" — are addressed with the argument that the God who clothes the grass will certainly clothe his people. Christ uses this tender address for disciples who lose courage (Matt 8:26; 14:31). He is the one who does not extinguish the smoldering wick (Matt 12:20); the little faith is not condemned but called to growth in trust.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme: the anxious questions — what shall we eat, drink, wear — will be answered in the feeding miracles and in the eschatological banquet (Matt 22:1–10; 26:29) that Christ prepares. The prohibition of anxious questioning is an implicit invitation to trust the one who will be the host at that table.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: "the pagans run after all these things" because they do not know the Father. The knowledge of the Father — his character as the providential giver — is what distinguishes the disciple community. This knowledge is not abstract theology but relational knowledge that Christ uniquely possesses and communicates: "no one knows the Father except the Son and anyone to whom the Son chooses to reveal him" (Matt 11:27).</p>',
    "33": '<p>A direct claim: "seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness" is the positive summary of 6:19–34. Seeking the kingdom means seeking the King — and Jesus announces throughout Matthew that the kingdom\'s arrival is inseparable from his own arrival (Matt 4:17; 12:28). The promise that "all these things will be added" is the covenant-faithfulness pledge of the God who provides, now mediated through the Son who is present. Seeking Christ is seeking the kingdom.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "tomorrow will worry about itself — each day has enough trouble of its own" closes the anxiety section with earthy wisdom: the God who designed the created order supplies enough grace for the present moment. Paul develops this into the sufficiency-in-all-circumstances of Phil 4:11–13: "I can do all things through him who strengthens me." The present-tense faithfulness of God is grounded in Christ\'s present-tense intercession (Heb 7:25).</p>'
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'matthew')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, MATTHEW_5_6)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'matthew', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Matthew mkt-christ: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
